# Linux installer for `ag`

## Context

`installers/` currently holds two mis-named scripts: `install.sh` is a Windows
PowerShell installer, and `install-windows-v1.0.0.ps1` is a Linux bash
installer. The bash installer is also out of date — it targets a stale
"Agentic RAG / fro" layout (binary `target/release/fro`, prefix
`~/.agentic-rag`, health probe on `localhost:3000/monitoring/health`) that
does not match the current project. Today the real shape is:

- Backend crate: `ag` (`backend/Cargo.toml` name=`ag`), binary at
  `target/release/ag`.
- Runtime base dir: `PathManager` (`backend/src/path_manager.rs:50`) uses
  `$AG_HOME`, falling back to `dirs::data_local_dir()/ag` → on Linux
  `~/.local/share/ag`. PathManager creates `data/`, `index/`, `db/`,
  `logs/`, `cache/`, `locks/` under that base dir.
- Process entrypoint: `start-ag.sh` (brings up the docker stack, fixes
  `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` for `libtika_native.so`, execs the binary).
- Systemd unit: `systemd/ag-full-stack.service` (user unit, hard-codes
  `/home/pde/ag`).
- Docker compose stack: `docker-compose.yml` with profiles `core`
  (Redis, Ollama) and `observability` (Prometheus, Grafana, Loki, Tempo,
  OTel collector).
- Health endpoint: `/health` on `BACKEND_PORT` (default `3010`)
  (`backend/src/api/mod.rs:705`, :796, :951).
- Config: `.env.example` is the canonical template — 200+ keys.
- FalkorDB (knowledge graph) is **not** a container — it runs as a native
  systemd user service `falkordb.service` (`redis-server` loading
  `falkordb.so` on `127.0.0.1:6380`). Binaries and data live at
  `$AG_HOME/falkordb/{redis-server,redis-cli,falkordb.so,data/}`. Rationale
  and verified setup: `docs/falkordb-native-service.md`. The binaries are
  extracted from the `falkordb/falkordb` Docker image — so even the
  "native" path needs Docker present at install time, even though the
  runtime no longer depends on `dockerd`.

### Two parallel systemd templates exist — installer commits to the XDG one

The repo carries **two checked-in `ag` systemd unit templates** that have
never been reconciled:

- `systemd/ag-full-stack.service` (19 lines, last touched April 30) — the
  "run in-place from the repo" model. Invokes `start-ag.sh`, hard-codes
  `/home/pde/ag` paths, and has drifted behind the live `ag.service` on
  dev boxes (missing `EnvironmentFile=`, `ExecStartPre=`, `LimitNOFILE=`,
  and the `NoNewPrivileges`/`PrivateTmp`/`ProtectSystem` hardening lines).
- `backend/src/ops/systemd/ag.service` (also touched April 30) — the
  XDG-style model. Binary at `%h/.local/bin/ag`, env at
  `%h/.config/ag/ag.env`, working dir at `%h/.local/share/ag`, full
  hardening, port-clearing `ExecStartPre`. Has never actually run a real
  install, but it's the closer-to-prod-quality file of the two.

This installer commits to the **XDG model**. `start-ag.sh`'s three jobs
split cleanly into systemd primitives:

- Locate `libtika_native.so` → copied out of the cargo build artifacts
  (`target/release/build/extractous-*/out/libs/`) at install time and
  placed at `~/.local/lib/`, picked up at runtime via
  `Environment=LD_LIBRARY_PATH=%h/.local/lib` in `ag.service`.
- `docker compose up -d` for the observability/cache stack → its own
  `ag-stack.service` user unit, with `ag.service` declaring
  `Wants=`/`After=` via a drop-in.
- `exec target/release/ag` → `ExecStart=%h/.local/bin/ag` in `ag.service`.

After install, the repo is no longer load-bearing: binary, libs, compose
file, frontend dist, env file, and FalkorDB binaries are all copied out
to XDG paths. The repo can be moved or deleted without breaking the
running system. `start-ag.sh` becomes dead code — kept on disk so the
existing dev-box `ag.service` keeps working through the transition, but
no installed unit references it. **Promotion plan:**
`backend/src/ops/systemd/ag.service` is promoted to
`systemd/ag.service.tmpl` (with placeholders for env/compose paths); the
old `systemd/ag-full-stack.service` is deleted.

Goal: produce one correct, well-named Linux installer (`install-linux.sh`)
that builds `ag`, copies binary + libraries + frontend assets + compose
file to XDG paths, sets up three composable systemd user units
(`falkordb.service`, `ag-stack.service`, `ag.service`), optionally
installs Docker itself if absent. Also clean up the installers-dir
file-name swap and remove the stale v1.1.0 bash script.

### External dependencies the installer does not create

The installer creates three user systemd units. Two more sit beside them
at runtime, owned outside the installer's scope:

- **`docker.service`** (system unit). Required for both `ag-stack.service`
  (`ExecStart=docker compose …`) and the one-shot FalkorDB binary
  extraction. Provided by the OS package or installed via the opt-in
  `--install-docker` step. The installer's templates declare
  `After=docker.service` but never touch the unit itself.
- **`ollama.service`** (user unit). Required at runtime for any
  LLM-backed agent mode (`Llm`, `Hybrid`, `Agentic`); `Rag` and
  `RagStrict` will still work without it. The installer **does not
  create this unit and explicitly does not call ollama's `install.sh`**.
  On this project's reference box, ollama is set up manually from a
  tarball, with `--exclude=lib/ollama/cuda_v*` because the host is CPU-
  only; ollama's `install.sh` would create a conflicting *system*
  `ollama.service` on port 11434 that can't see the user's existing
  models. The installer's behavior:
  - Preflight: detect whether `ollama.service` (user) is active; if not,
    treat it as a **soft** warning, not a failure — install proceeds,
    LLM-dependent endpoints will surface their own 503s at use time.
  - Final summary: if ollama wasn't detected, print a one-liner pointing
    at the manual-tarball flow (see the auto-memory reference
    `reference-ollama-setup`, or whatever doc lands at `docs/ollama-native-service.md`
    if one is written later).
  - Never invoke `curl … install.sh | sh`-style flows for ollama.

`OLLAMA_URL` and `OLLAMA_MODEL` in `.env.example` are the canonical pointers
ag uses to reach ollama; they're seeded into `~/.config/ag/ag.env` as
part of the seed-config step and remain user-editable from there.

## Defaults chosen (these are the redirect points)

- **Scope**: the installer runs **five** steps by default — build backend,
  build frontend, install artifacts to XDG paths, set up FalkorDB native
  service, install + enable the three systemd user units (`ag.service`,
  `ag-stack.service`, `falkordb.service`). Each step has a `--no-*` flag
  where it makes sense (`--no-frontend`, `--no-falkordb`, `--no-stack`,
  `--no-systemd`); `--with-stack=PROFILE` selects a compose profile that
  `ag-stack.service` will apply.
- **Layout**: **XDG-clean**. After install, the repo is not load-bearing
  — it can be moved or deleted without breaking the running system.
  Specifically:
  - `~/.local/bin/ag` — the binary
  - `~/.local/lib/libtika_native.so` — Apache Tika native lib (copied out
    of `target/release/build/extractous-*/out/libs/`; symlink the
    versioned file if any, plus the bare `libtika_native.so` name the
    binary dlopens)
  - `~/.local/share/ag/web/` — frontend dist (copied from
    `frontend/fro/dist/`)
  - `~/.local/share/ag/falkordb/{redis-server,redis-cli,falkordb.so,data/}`
    — Redis + FalkorDB module binaries + data
  - `~/.config/ag/ag.env` — env file (seeded from repo `.env.example`)
  - `~/.config/ag/docker-compose.yml` — copied from repo so the stack
    unit doesn't reach back into the source tree
  - `~/.config/systemd/user/{ag,ag-stack,falkordb}.service` — three units
  - `~/.local/share/ag/{data,index,db,logs,cache,locks}` — runtime state
    (matches `PathManager`)
- **No `sudo`** for the default path. All systemd units are `--user`
  units; all writes land under `$HOME`. Root is only needed for the
  **opt-in** `--install-docker` step.
- **`start-ag.sh` is no longer invoked by any installed unit.** The file
  stays on disk so existing dev-box `ag.service` units that still
  reference it keep working. New installs use `ag.service` (XDG)
  + `ag-stack.service` for the compose stack.
- **Use existing software.** The installer's governing principle is
  reuse what's already on the box. **Verifiable** reuses (binary sha
  match, libtika mtime, healthy FalkorDB, active Ollama, docker
  present, existing `ag.env`, warm cargo / target/, etc.) fire
  silently. **Non-verifiable** reuses (active native observability,
  system Redis on 6379, divergent existing `ag.service`) prompt with
  "use existing" as the default; the post-install summary lists what
  was reused and what assumptions weren't checkable (`⚠`). The default
  install on a clean machine still runs to completion without prompts;
  prompts only appear when existing state was detected.
  `--non-interactive` collapses prompts to their defaults;
  `--force-fresh` overrides every reuse. See "Detection and reuse
  policy" in §Implementation notes.
- **Docker installation is opt-in.** Most users already have Docker, the
  install requires `sudo`, the official script touches package manager
  state, and it can need a logout/login for group membership to take
  effect. Default behavior: preflight requires `docker` on PATH (since
  FalkorDB binary extraction needs it); if missing and `--install-docker`
  was not passed, the installer fails with a clear pointer at
  `--install-docker` or the Docker docs.

