## Disk footprint

Measured on the reference dev box (Linux glibc, Rust 1.x release build).
The installer should print these numbers in the post-install summary so
users can size cleanups, and should refuse to start in preflight if free
space is dangerously low.

**Three install scenarios.** The headline number depends heavily on
what the reuse policy (§Detection and reuse policy) finds already on
the host. Cold-cache fresh box is the worst case; warm-cache rerun on
an existing install adds almost nothing.

| Scenario | New disk used | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Cold-cache fresh box | ~14.5 GB persistent / ~17 GB transient peak | First-time cargo build, first-time docker pulls, first-time FalkorDB extraction, fresh `~/.cargo` registry. See breakdown below. |
| Warm-cache re-run (this box now) | ~200 MB | Tier 1 auto-reuse fires for everything: docker images cached, FalkorDB healthy (skip), `ag.env` kept, compose state idempotent. Net new on disk: the binary + libtika + frontend dist in their XDG paths, plus a small cargo incremental delta. |
| Half-warm (fresh XDG, populated repo) | ~2.5 GB | Repo's `target/` and `~/.cargo` already exist; docker images already pulled. New: XDG artifacts (~260 MB) + ~2 GB of docker images if compose was never run + nothing else. |

What each Tier 1 reuse saves vs. cold-cache:

- **Docker images already pulled** → ~1.5 GB of disk + ~1.5 GB of network skipped
- **FalkorDB healthy** → 640 MB image not pulled (if also already cached) + 78 MB extraction skipped + ~5–10s of work skipped
- **`~/.cargo` warm** → 1–2 GB of registry growth avoided
- **`target/` warm** → ~10 GB of cold-cache cargo work becomes incremental (~100 MB to 1 GB depending on what changed)
- **Existing `ag.env`** → no disk saving, but config edits preserved
- **Compose stack already up** → 0 disk impact (`docker compose up -d` is idempotent)

**Persistent after install (cold cache, no cleanup) ≈ 14.5 GB:**

| Where | What | Size |
|---|---|---|
| `~/.local/bin/ag` | release binary | 63 MB |
| `~/.local/lib/libtika_native.so` | Apache Tika JNI lib | 110 MB |
| `~/.local/share/ag/falkordb/` | redis-server, redis-cli, falkordb.so (empty data dir) | 78 MB |
| `~/.local/share/ag/web/` | frontend dist (wasm + JS) | 10 MB |
| `~/.config/ag/` | env file + compose file + units | <1 MB |
| Docker images: compose stack | grafana 577 + prometheus 352 + otelcol 309 + tempo 153 + loki 101 + redis 61 | 1.5 GB |
| Docker images: `falkordb/falkordb:latest` | needed for extraction; installer leaves it cached | 640 MB |
| `target/` | kept for incremental rebuilds | 10 GB |
| `~/.cargo` | registry cache; shared across all Rust projects | 2.2 GB |
| `frontend/fro/node_modules` | npm deps | 37 MB |

**Minimum persistent (aggressive cleanup) ≈ 2.4 GB:**

After `cargo clean` + `docker image rm falkordb/falkordb:latest`
(extraction image is unused at runtime), the steady-state footprint is
~260 MB of XDG-installed artifacts + ~1.5 GB of compose docker images.
`~/.cargo` is shared across Rust projects so attributing it to ag isn't
honest.

**Transient peak during install ≈ 17 GB:**

- Cargo build working set on a fresh-box (no prior cache): ~10–12 GB at
  peak inside `target/`
- Cargo registry growth: ~1–2 GB into `~/.cargo`
- Docker image pulls: ~2 GB

These overlap in time, not just sum. After the build finishes and the
pulls complete, usage settles to one of the two figures above.

**Runtime growth — not included** (depends on use):

- FalkorDB AOF + RDB in `~/.local/share/ag/falkordb/data/` — KB to GB,
  scales with graph size.
- Tantivy index in `~/.local/share/ag/index/` — MB to GB, scales with
  corpus.
- Loki / Tempo / Prometheus Docker volumes — hundreds of MB per month
  under active use.
- ag application logs in `~/.local/share/ag/logs/` — bounded by log
  rotation.

### Preflight disk check (hard, gated by `--skip-checks`)

Run `df -P "$HOME"` and `df -P "$PROJECT_PATH"`, take the **minimum**
available across the two (they're usually the same filesystem on a
workstation but not always). Three thresholds:

| Free space | Behavior |
|---|---|
| ≥ 20 GB | Green. Proceed silently. |
| 10–20 GB | Yellow. Warn: `install peaks ~17 GB; you have N GB free on $FS. Proceed? (y/N)` — answered by `--non-interactive` defaulting to "no" (refuse, exit clean). |
| < 10 GB | Red. Refuse with exit 1 unless `--skip-checks` was passed. Message: `< 10 GB free on $FS; install would almost certainly fail mid-build. Run \`cargo clean\` or free up space first, or re-run with --skip-checks to override.` |

Threshold reasoning: the 10 GB floor matches the typical cargo build
peak; below that the build will hit `No space left on device` partway
through, leaving a half-installed state to clean up. 20 GB gives 1.3x
headroom for the full transient peak — enough that an active swap file
or a parallel build elsewhere won't push the host into low-disk
pressure mid-install.

**These thresholds assume cold-cache.** A warm-cache re-run on an
existing install needs ~200 MB of new disk, not 17 GB. To avoid
false-positive refusals on warm-cache machines with tight free space,
the disk check **runs after preflight tool detection but before the
detection phase writes anything**, and downgrades by tier:

- If `target/` already exists with a recent successful build (mtime on
  `target/release/ag` newer than `Cargo.lock`): drop the threshold to
  **5 GB free / 2 GB hard floor** — incremental build needs almost
  nothing.
- If FalkorDB is healthy AND all compose images are already pulled:
  the FalkorDB image (640 MB) and compose pulls (1.5 GB) won't happen
  → drop the threshold by 2 GB.
- Both conditions met: 3 GB free is enough to finish. Hard floor:
  1 GB.

The check still refuses if any layer of caching is missing and the
host has < 10 GB free, since the cargo build alone needs that.

The disk check runs *before* the detection phase's prompts — no point
asking about prompt defaults if the install can't possibly finish.

## Implementation notes for the new `install-linux.sh`

Keep the shape of the old script (set -euo pipefail, color logger,
`--help`/`--version`, log file). Differences from the v1.1.0 file that
matter:

### Progress reporting

The default install is mostly stretches of underlying-tool output (cargo
crate-by-crate, npm spinner, docker layer-pull bars). Without a frame
around them, the user can't tell which step they're inside when they
scroll back, and can't tell how long a step took. Three cheap conventions
the installer enforces on its own log lines (not on the underlying tools'
output):

- **Step counter prefix** on every step header:
  `[N/TOTAL] ► <step name>` where `TOTAL` is the live count of enabled
  steps (5 default; drops as `--no-*` flags are passed; rises to 6 with
  `--install-docker`). Print this immediately *before* invoking the
  step's underlying tool so it's visible above the cargo/npm/docker
  output that follows.
- **Per-step duration** on the step-completed line:
  `[N/TOTAL] ✓ <step name>  (Ns)` — recorded with `SECONDS` between the
  step's start and end. Failed steps print `✗` with the same shape so the
  duration is visible even on failure.
- **Pinned log file path** — chosen up front as
  `${AG_HOME}/logs/install-$(date -u +%Y%m%dT%H%M%SZ).log`, created
  before any step runs, and `tee`'d to. Print the absolute path in the
  startup banner *and again* in the final summary, so the user always
  knows where to look when underlying-tool output drowned out an error.
  On failure (`trap ERR`), print the log path one more time with a
  pointer at the last 50 lines.

These are installer-side only — don't try to wrap `cargo`/`npm`/`docker`
output in step prefixes. They stream to the terminal as they always do;
the prefixes bracket them.

### Completion notification

Cold-cache install runs ~20–30 minutes. Users walk away. The installer
fires two notifications when it finishes (success or failure), both
best-effort, both silent on failure:

- **Terminal bell** — `printf '\a' > /dev/tty` in a subshell that
  swallows bash's redirect-failure message when /dev/tty isn't
  available (CI, `bash <(...)`, etc.).
- **`notify-send`** — desktop notification. `--urgency=critical` on
  failure (red icon, doesn't auto-dismiss on most desktops);
  `--urgency=normal` on success.

Fires from `print_summary` on success and from the `on_error` trap on
failure. The body text includes elapsed time on success and the log
file path + exit line on failure, so the notification alone is enough
context for the user to know what happened without opening the
terminal.

### Detection and reuse policy

The installer is not assuming a clean slate. The governing principle:
**use what's already there.** Before every write, detect existing state
and decide based on whether the reuse is **verifiable** (the installer
can confirm the existing software is correct for ag's needs) or
**non-verifiable** (correctness depends on configuration the installer
can't introspect from outside).

- **Verifiable reuse** → silent. Log it in the post-install summary so
  the user can audit, but don't ask.
- **Non-verifiable reuse** → prompt with sensible default. Default
  toward reuse when active state suggests the user has chosen this
  configuration deliberately.
- **No existing state** → install fresh.
- **`--force-fresh`** overrides every reuse decision. **`--non-interactive`**
  applies defaults silently on prompts.

**Verifiable reuses — silent + logged:**

| Component | Verification | Reuse behavior |
|---|---|---|
| `~/.local/bin/ag` ⏳ *Phase 2* | `sha256` of binary vs sha embedded by build (compare against `git rev-parse HEAD`) | Skip rebuild AND skip copy; the install is already current. **Phase 1: always rebuild** (cargo incremental is cheap); copy step uses mtime. |
| `~/.local/share/ag/web/` frontend ⏳ *Phase 2* | wasm hash in filename matches what trunk would produce from current HEAD | Skip frontend build + rsync. **Phase 1: always rebuild**; rsync uses mtime / `--checksum`. |
| `~/.local/lib/libtika_native.so` | mtime newer than `target/release/build/extractous-*/out/libs/libtika_native.so` source | Skip copy. |
| Docker | `command -v docker` | Use it. |
| Ollama (user) | `systemctl --user is-active ollama` AND `curl -fsS http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/tags` succeeds | Use it. |
| Compose stack already up | `docker compose ls` shows our project name | No-op (`docker compose up -d` is idempotent anyway). |
| FalkorDB healthy | `falkordb.service` active AND `redis-cli -p $FDB_PORT -a $FDB_PASS ping` returns `PONG` | Skip extraction, skip unit install. Data dir untouched. |
| `~/.config/ag/ag.env` | file present | Keep — never overwrite. New keys added in `.env.example` since last install are listed in the summary as "merge candidates" — not auto-merged. |
| `target/`, `~/.cargo` | mtime / presence | Implicit — cargo handles incremental build and registry reuse on its own. No installer logic needed; just don't `cargo clean` first. |

**Non-verifiable reuses — prompt with sensible default:**

| Component | Trigger | Prompt + default |
|---|---|---|
| Native observability stack active | any of `loki`/`tempo`/`otelcol` is `systemctl --user is-active` AND its expected port responds | `[U]se natives` *(default)* — skip `ag-stack.service`, point ag.env at the native endpoints (installer prints the assumed URLs; user confirms) / `[I]nstall compose alongside` (compose units on alternate ports — only offered if no port conflict) / `[S]top natives and use compose` / `[A]bort install`. **⚠** logged: "you said use natives — verify your scrape config covers ag.service `/metrics`, your retention policy is what you expect, etc." **Phase 1 caveat:** Loki isn't configurable separately — logs flow through OTel collector → Loki, so "use native Loki" only takes effect via `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`. The native-Loki branch is offered only when *also* using native OTel. Phase 2 adds a separate `LOKI_URL` once ag has a direct Loki client. |
| System Redis on `127.0.0.1:6379` | `redis-cli -p 6379 ping` returns `PONG` | `[U]se system Redis` *(default)* — write `REDIS_URL=redis://127.0.0.1:6379` into ag.env, skip `ag-redis` from compose / `[I]nstall ag-redis (compose) anyway` (parallel cache on 6380). **⚠** logged: "auth config not verified — set `REDIS_PASSWORD` in ag.env if your Redis requires it." |
| System `redis-server` for FalkorDB fallback | only triggered if the extracted FalkorDB binary failed the host smoke-test (musl/glibc mismatch); check `redis-server --version` for Redis 7.x | `[U]se system redis-server with extracted falkordb.so` *(default)* — write a falkordb.service variant that loads the system `redis-server` binary / `[A]bort, set up FalkorDB manually` (see `docs/falkordb-native-service.md` §2). |
| Existing `ag.service` with different content | unit file exists and `diff` against the rendered template is non-empty | `[K]eep existing` *(default)* / `[B]ackup → ag.service.bak-<ts> and replace` / `[R]eplace without backup`. Live hand-edits accumulate over time; "keep" is the safe default. |
| Existing `ag-stack.service` differs | same | Same shape as `ag.service`. |
| `--purge` on uninstall | always | y/N before deleting `$AG_HOME`. `--purge --yes` for scripted use; **`--non-interactive` does NOT override this** — data loss is irreversible. |

**Install a second copy in parallel — out of scope for v1.** A second
binary at `~/.local/bin/ag-v2` + `ag-v2.service` on an alternate port is
meaningful for A/B testing across versions, but it's a deliberate dev
workflow. Don't surface it in v1; revisit if it ever comes up as a real
ask. (The "install ag-redis alongside system Redis" prompt option above
is a narrower exception — Redis-on-alt-port is cheap and useful when
the user has a system Redis with auth they don't want to share.)

**Post-install summary always shows three explicit lists:**

```
✓ Reused (silent):      docker, ollama, ~/.cargo, target/, ag.env, libtika
✓ Reused (confirmed):   native-loki at :3100, native-tempo at :3200,
                        system-redis at :6379
+ Installed fresh:      ag.service, ag-stack.service (only OTel + Grafana
                        + Prometheus — others reused above),
                        falkordb.service (binaries extracted from image)
⚠ Reused with assumption:
    native-loki at :3100   — verify your scrape config covers
                             ag.service's /metrics endpoint
    system-redis at :6379  — auth not verified; set REDIS_PASSWORD
                             in ag.env if your Redis requires it
```

The `⚠` block is the audit hook: anything reused that the installer
couldn't fully verify gets called out, with the specific assumption to
check. A user who reviews this list at end-of-install will catch the
configuration gaps that aggressive reuse otherwise hides.

**Observability deployment choice — the default flipped to natives**

Earlier drafts had compose as the default with `--reuse-observability`
as opt-in. Under the "use existing software" principle, the default
flips: if native loki/tempo/otelcol units are *active* (not merely
installed), prefer them, prompt the user, default to using them. Compose
fills in only for services without an active native equivalent.

Rationale for the flip:

- An *active* native unit is strong evidence the user chose this setup
  deliberately. Replacing it surprises more than serving it does.
- Installer-side endpoint inference is cheap: each native unit's port
  is in its unit file's `ExecStart`. The installer reads them and
  writes the corresponding URLs into `ag.env`. No guesswork on the
  user's part beyond confirming the prompt.
- The retention / scrape / config concerns become a single `⚠` line in
  the summary, not a reason to refuse reuse.
- *Inactive* natives still default to compose — they're noise, not a
  signal of user intent.

The flag `--reuse-observability` is removed (default behavior subsumes
it). The new opt-out is `--force-compose`: ignore native units even if
active, always install `ag-stack.service` for the full stack.

**The `--non-interactive` flag.** All Tier 2 prompts apply their default
silently when `--non-interactive` is passed (or env
`AG_INSTALL_NONINTERACTIVE=1` is set). This restores the "default
install runs to completion without prompts" behavior for CI / scripted
installs at the cost of taking the conservative default everywhere.
`--purge` always prompts — `--non-interactive` does *not* override
that, since the consequence is irreversible data loss and there's a
separate `--purge --yes` for the truly automated case.

**Detection-phase placement.** All detection runs in a single phase
*before* any step writes to disk, with results cached in shell
variables for later use. The new shape:

```
parse flags → preflight → DETECT → confirm prompts → execute steps
```

This means: if there are three prompts, the user answers all three up
front, then walks away. Long-running build steps don't pause asking for
input two-thirds of the way in. The detection phase also gates the
flow — if `[A]bort install` is chosen at any prompt, no writes happen
at all.

- `AG_HOME` default → `$HOME/.local/share/ag`. Match
  `PathManager::get_base_dir` exactly so the installer's directories are
  the ones the running binary actually uses. Drop the
  `documents.db`/`memory.db` touch — those aren't real schemas; let the
  app create what it needs on first boot.
- Runtime-state subdirs under `AG_HOME`: `data index db logs cache locks
  web falkordb falkordb/data` (PathManager dirs + `web/` for frontend
  dist + `falkordb/` for the native graph store).
- Don't touch `~/.bashrc`/`.zshrc`. Instead write `~/.config/ag/ag.env`
  by copying `.env.example` and overwriting `BACKEND_HOST` /
  `BACKEND_PORT` / `AG_HOME` if `--backend-port` / `--prefix` are passed.
  `AG_HOME` doesn't need to be in the shell — the systemd unit's
  `EnvironmentFile=` reads `ag.env`. The startup banner prints a one-line
  `export AG_HOME=…` for interactive-shell parity; optional.
- Compose-file copy: `install -m 0644 docker-compose.yml
  ~/.config/ag/docker-compose.yml` (only if absent — never overwrite user
  edits). This is what lets the repo become deletable after install. If
  the file already exists and differs from the repo's version, log a
  warning with `diff` summary; don't silently overwrite, don't fail.
- Backend build: `cargo build --release` from the repo root (workspace
  default-member is `backend`, so this builds `ag`). Verify
  `target/release/ag` exists; print its size.
- Frontend build (default; skip with `--no-frontend`): `cd frontend/fro &&
  npm ci && npm run css:build && trunk build --release`. Refuse with a
  clear error if `trunk` or `npm` is missing — don't try to install them.
- Install artifacts to XDG paths (always runs after build steps):
  - `install -m 0755 target/release/ag ~/.local/bin/ag` — atomic replace,
    survives in-place updates with the unit running (systemd re-execs on
    next restart).
  - `libtika_native.so` lives under `target/release/build/extractous-*/out/libs/`
    with a build-hash directory name that changes per build. Find the
    **newest** match (`ls -td target/release/build/extractous-*/out/libs |
    head -n1`), copy `libtika_native.so` to `~/.local/lib/`. Abort if
    multiple candidates and none has a clear "newest" — surface the
    paths and let the user pick.
  - Frontend dist (only if `--no-frontend` was not passed):
    `rsync -a --delete frontend/fro/dist/ ~/.local/share/ag/web/`.
    `--delete` so stale assets from prior builds get cleaned up; the
    target dir is wholly owned by the installer.
  - Final smoke-test of the installed binary, no daemon involved:
    `LD_LIBRARY_PATH=~/.local/lib ~/.local/bin/ag --version`. If this
    fails with "cannot open shared object file: libtika_native.so", the
    libtika copy step is broken — abort here, *before* installing
    systemd units that would just keep restarting.
- Systemd unit rendering (default; skip with `--no-systemd`):
  - `ag.service`: `sed` `systemd/ag.service.tmpl` to substitute
    `{{AG_BIN}}` → `$HOME/.local/bin/ag`, `{{AG_HOME}}` →
    `$HOME/.local/share/ag`, `{{AG_ENV}}` → `$HOME/.config/ag/ag.env`,
    `{{AG_LIB_DIR}}` → `$HOME/.local/lib`. Use **literal paths**, not
    `%h` — keeps the rendered unit readable for users debugging via
    `systemctl --user cat ag.service`. Install to
    `~/.config/systemd/user/ag.service`.
  - `ag-stack.service` (skip with `--no-stack`): `sed`
    `systemd/ag-stack.service.tmpl` to substitute `{{COMPOSE_FILE}}` →
    `$HOME/.config/ag/docker-compose.yml`, `{{COMPOSE_PROFILE}}` →
    `$WITH_STACK` (the `--with-stack=` value, default empty string =
    all services). Install to `~/.config/systemd/user/ag-stack.service`.
  - Drop-ins (`ag.service.d/falkordb.conf`, `ag.service.d/stack.conf`)
    install from the repo's `systemd/ag.service.d/` to
    `~/.config/systemd/user/ag.service.d/`. Skip `falkordb.conf` if
    `--no-falkordb`. Skip `stack.conf` if `--no-stack`.
  - `systemctl --user daemon-reload`, then
    `systemctl --user enable --now ag-stack.service` (if installed) and
    `systemctl --user enable --now ag.service`. Don't enable lingering —
    that's a separate user decision.
- Health check: poll `http://127.0.0.1:${BACKEND_PORT}/health` up to 10x
  at 2s intervals. Treat "no response" as a warning, not a hard failure,
  because the user might have passed `--no-systemd` and not started the
  service themselves yet.
- Don't run `cargo test` as part of install. That's what the
  user's quality-gate (`cargo fmt && cargo clippy`) is for and it doubles
  install time. The old script did this; we drop it.
- Don't try to start a verification `cargo run` and then `kill` it (the
  old script's "post-build verification"). The artifact smoke-test above
  (`ag --version`) covers the "binary loads its libs" question without a
  daemon, and the systemd health check covers the "service actually
  came up" question. Together they replace the old hack.

### Docker install (opt-in, `--install-docker`)

- Refuse if not running on a glibc Linux with a recognized package manager
  (Debian/Ubuntu/Fedora/Arch). Don't try to be clever on exotic distros —
  point the user at the Docker docs.
- Use Docker's official convenience script: `curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com
  -o /tmp/get-docker.sh && sudo sh /tmp/get-docker.sh`. Prompt for sudo
  once, up front, so the rest of the install isn't interleaved with
  password prompts.
- After install: `sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"` + `sudo systemctl
  enable --now docker`. Then **warn loudly** that the user must either log
  out and back in or run `newgrp docker` before the subsequent steps in
  this same installer run will see the new group membership. The simplest
  honest move: if the installer started without docker group access, exit
  cleanly with that instruction after installing Docker, and have the user
  re-invoke. Don't try to `sudo -u "$USER" ...` the rest of the pipeline.
- If Docker is already present, `--install-docker` is a no-op (log it,
  don't fail).

### FalkorDB native service (default; `--no-falkordb` skips)

- Require `docker` on PATH (used only to extract binaries — runtime is
  native). If `--install-docker` was passed earlier in the same run, this
  step is what justified it.
- Extraction paths inside the image are version-sensitive. The current
  verified locations (from the `falkordb/falkordb:latest` image as of the
  native-service migration) are
  `/usr/local/bin/redis-server`, `/usr/local/bin/redis-cli`,
  `/var/lib/falkordb/bin/falkordb.so`. If `docker cp` fails with "no such
  file", probe with `docker run --rm --entrypoint sh falkordb/falkordb
  -c 'command -v redis-server; find / -name falkordb.so 2>/dev/null'` and
  surface a clear error pointing at this paragraph — don't silently
  install nothing.
- After `docker cp`, **smoke-test on the host before installing the
  unit**: `chmod +x ${AG_HOME}/falkordb/redis-server &&
  ${AG_HOME}/falkordb/redis-server --version`. If this fails with an ELF /
  loader error, the image is musl-based and the extracted binaries won't
  run on glibc. Abort with the fallback options from
  `docs/falkordb-native-service.md` §2: a distro `redis-server` + a built
  `falkordb.so`, or build FalkorDB from source. Don't try to auto-fall-back
  — surface the choice.
- Render `systemd/falkordb.service.tmpl` → `~/.config/systemd/user/falkordb.service`
  with `sed`, substituting `{{AG_HOME}}`, `{{FDB_PORT}}` (default `6380`),
  `{{FDB_PASS}}` (default `agpassword123` for parity with the verified
  unit; overridable via `--falkordb-password`). The `ExecStart` line stays
  identical in shape to the verified unit (`--port`, `--bind 127.0.0.1`,
  `--requirepass`, `--appendonly yes`, `--dir`, `--loadmodule`).
- `systemctl --user daemon-reload && systemctl --user enable --now
  falkordb.service`.
- Final smoke-test: `${AG_HOME}/falkordb/redis-cli -p $FDB_PORT -a
  $FDB_PASS ping` — expect `PONG`. Treat failure here as hard: the rest of
  the install assumes FalkorDB is reachable, and `ag.service`'s `Wants=`
  will surface the same failure later anyway.
- **Don't overwrite an existing healthy service.** If
  `~/.config/systemd/user/falkordb.service` already exists and
  `redis-cli ... ping` returns `PONG`, log "FalkorDB already running" and
  skip extraction + unit install. The data dir is precious; never touch
  `${AG_HOME}/falkordb/data/`.
- The `ag.service` drop-in (`systemd/ag.service.d/falkordb.conf`) gets
  installed to `~/.config/systemd/user/ag.service.d/falkordb.conf` as
  part of the systemd step, not here — but skip the drop-in install if
  `--no-falkordb` was passed.

### `ag-stack.service` (default; `--no-stack` skips)

Wraps `docker compose up -d`/`down` as a oneshot systemd user unit so
the compose stack has the same `journalctl --user -u` ergonomics as
`ag` and `falkordb`, and so `ag.service` can declare a real dependency
on it via the `stack.conf` drop-in.

Template shape (`systemd/ag-stack.service.tmpl`):

```ini
[Unit]
Description=ag — docker compose stack (observability, redis, …)
After=docker.service network-online.target
Wants=docker.service network-online.target

[Service]
Type=oneshot
RemainAfterExit=yes
ExecStart=/usr/bin/docker compose -f {{COMPOSE_FILE}} \
    --profile {{COMPOSE_PROFILE}} up -d
ExecStop=/usr/bin/docker compose -f {{COMPOSE_FILE}} \
    --profile {{COMPOSE_PROFILE}} down
TimeoutStartSec=300

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
```

Notes:

- `Type=oneshot` + `RemainAfterExit=yes` is the canonical pattern for
  "this command brings up state that persists; treat the unit as active
  while that state is up." `systemctl --user status ag-stack.service`
  will show "active (exited)" after the up completes.
- `After=docker.service` is a soft ordering hint; on a non-systemd-Docker
  setup (rare) it's a no-op. `network-online.target` matters for the
  first image pull on a fresh box.
- `TimeoutStartSec=300` is to cover the first-time-Ollama-image-pull
  case, which can take minutes.
- The renderer leaves an empty `--profile ""` arg when
  `--with-stack` was unset; compose treats empty profile as "all
  services with no profile constraint", which matches the previous
  install behavior. If `--with-stack=core` was passed, the rendered
  unit ends up with `--profile core`.
- **Why not `Restart=on-failure`?** `docker compose up -d` exits as soon
  as the compose has been brought up; there's nothing to restart. The
  compose services restart themselves via their own healthcheck/policy.
- **Why not in `ag.service` itself?** Decoupling means a binary crash
  doesn't bring the stack down (so Grafana stays reachable for
  debugging), and `systemctl --user restart ag.service` doesn't churn
  the stack.

### Retiring `start-ag.sh`

Don't reference `start-ag.sh` from any installed unit. The file stays on
disk so existing dev-box `ag.service` units that point at it keep
working; the uninstaller doesn't remove it either. A short header comment
is added marking it deprecated, with a pointer at this doc.

A separate cleanup commit — not part of installer landing — will delete
`start-ag.sh` once `git grep start-ag.sh` returns no live references in
the repo or in any tracked systemd unit.

